Online Course Student Engagement Project

Data for this project was obtained from the Predict Online Course Engagement Dataset by Kaggle.com user Rabie El Kharoua.

The dataset is available through a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0) license.

Description of the dataset's features, from the Data Card:

  • UserID: Unique identifier for each user
  • CourseCategory: Category of the course taken by the user (e.g., Programming, Business, Arts)
  • TimeSpentOnCourse: Total time spent by the user on the course in hours
  • NumberOfVideosWatched: Total number of videos watched by the user
  • NumberOfQuizzesTaken: Total number of quizzes taken by the user
  • QuizScores: Average scores achieved by the user in quizzes (percentage)
  • CompletionRate: Percentage of course content completed by the user
  • DeviceType: Type of device used by the user (0: Desktop, 1: Mobile)
  • CourseCompletion (Target Variable): Course completion status (0: Not Completed, 1: Completed)

# Create pie charts to visualize distribution of categorical variables
def create_pie_chart(df, column, title, labels=None):
    counts = df[column].value_counts()
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
    plt.pie(counts, labels=counts.index if labels is None else labels, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140, colors=sns.color_palette('plasma'))
    plt.title(title)
    plt.axis('equal')
    plt.show()

create_pie_chart(df, 'CourseCategory', 'Distribution of Course Categories')
create_pie_chart(df, 'DeviceType', 'Distribution of Device Types', labels=['Desktop', 'Mobile'])
create_pie_chart(df, 'CourseCompletion', 'Distribution of Course Completion', labels=['Not Completed', 'Completed'])

In[16]:
# Encode categorical column and scale numerical columns
# Note: DeviceType is categorical, but it is already encoded numerically

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, LabelEncoder

# Encode categorical column 'CourseCategory'
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
df['CourseCategory'] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df['CourseCategory'])

# Apply scaling to numerical columns
scaler = StandardScaler()
numerical_columns = ['TimeSpentOnCourse', 'NumberOfVideosWatched', 
                    'NumberOfQuizzesTaken', 'QuizScores', 'CompletionRate']
df[numerical_columns] = scaler.fit_transform(df[numerical_columns])

In[17]:
# Preprocess data for model training

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Create dataframes X and y to separate the feature columns from the target column
X = df.drop('CourseCompletion', axis=1)
y = df['CourseCompletion']

# Split the data into testing and training sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=56)

Model Development

In[18]:
# Compare model performance
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier, AdaBoostClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from catboost import CatBoostClassifier

# Silence Warnings
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

np.random.seed(56)

# List of classification models
classification_models = [
    ('Logistic Regression', LogisticRegression()),
    ('K-Nearest Neighbors', KNeighborsClassifier()),
    ('Support Vector Machine', SVC()),
    ('Decision Tree', DecisionTreeClassifier()),
    ('Random Forest', RandomForestClassifier()),
    ('Gradient Boosting', GradientBoostingClassifier()),
    ('AdaBoost', AdaBoostClassifier()),
    ('Gaussian Naive Bayes', GaussianNB()),
    ('XGBoost', XGBClassifier()),
    ('CatBoost', CatBoostClassifier(silent=True))
]

results = []

# Train and evaluate each model
for name, model in classification_models:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    results.append((name, accuracy, precision, recall, f1))

# Create a DataFrame for model metrics
df_models = pd.DataFrame(results, columns=['Model', 'Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1 Score'])
In[19]:
# Compare model performance with a bar plot
results_melted = df_models.melt(id_vars='Model', var_name='Metric', value_name='Score')

# Set the plot size
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

# Create a bar plot grouped by model
sns.barplot(data=results_melted, x='Model', y='Score', hue='Metric', palette='inferno')

# Add title and labels
plt.title('Model Performance Comparison')
plt.xlabel('Model')
plt.ylabel('Score')
plt.ylim(0, 1)  # Assuming the metrics are all between 0 and 1
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Show the plot
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In[20]:
# Compare model performance with a heatmap, highest scores highlighted
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(df_models.set_index('Model'), annot=True, cmap='inferno', linewidths=.5, fmt=".3f")

# Highlight the highest score for each metric
for i, metric in enumerate(df_models.columns[1:]):
    idx = df_models[metric].idxmax()
    plt.gca().add_patch(plt.Rectangle((i, idx), 1, 1, fill=False, edgecolor='#c03a51', lw=3))

plt.title('Model Performance Metrics')
plt.xlabel('Metric')
plt.ylabel('Model')
plt.show()

# Focus on RandomForest model only

# Extract feature importances
rf_importances = rf_model.feature_importances_

# Display feature importances values
rf_feature_importances = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': rf_model.feature_names_in_ ,
                                    'Importance': rf_importances})
rf_feature_importances_sorted = rf_feature_importances.sort_values(by = ['Importance'], ascending = False).reset_index(drop=True)
